<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="118" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="118" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. F. Blake" authorityYear="1924" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gochnatia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Gochnatia obtusata" order="Asterales" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obtusata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Gochnatia obtusata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by S. F. 
<bibRefCitation author="Blake, SF" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the United States National Herbarium" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" pagination="587 - 661" publicationUrl="https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/381906" refId="B1" refString="Blake, SF, 1924. New American Asteraceae. Contributions from the United States National Herbarium 22 (8): 587 - 661, https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/381906" title="New American Asteraceae." url="https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/381906" volume="22" year="1924">Blake (1924)</bibRefCitation>
and accepted as a good species by 
<bibRefCitation author="Jervis, RN" journalOrPublisher="8. Eudicots-Asterales. Springer-Verlag, Berlin, Heidelberg" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" refId="B12" refString="Jervis, RN, 1954. A summary of the genus Gochnatia including a revision of the West Indian species which comprise the Section Anastraphioides. University of Michigan: unpublished thesis." title="A summary of the genus Gochnatia including a revision of the West Indian species which comprise the Section Anastraphioides. University of Michigan: unpublished thesis." year="1954">Jervis (1954)</bibRefCitation>
. Cabrera placed it as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. hypoleuca" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" rank="species" species="hypoleuca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">G. hypoleuca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as did 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/3298594" author="Freire, SE" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" pagination="525 - 550" refId="B7" refString="Freire, SE, Katinas, L, Sancho, G, 2002. Gochnatia (Asteraceae: Mutisieae) and the Gochnatia complex: taxonomic implications from morphology. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 89 (4): 525 - 550, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/3298594" title="Gochnatia (Asteraceae: Mutisieae) and the Gochnatia complex: taxonomic implications from morphology." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3298594" volume="89" year="2002">Freire et al. (2002)</bibRefCitation>
. The difference of opinion is based on the importance one gives to the characters that separate the two entities. Blake stated that 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. hypoleuca" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" rank="species" species="hypoleuca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">G. hypoleuca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be separated from 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. obtusata" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" rank="species" species="obtusata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">G. obtusata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following characters: leaves chiefly elliptic, apex acute or acutish and mucronate, 20-50 mm 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8-15 mm; involucre 5-6 mm tall, phyllaries obtuse to acute or obtusely acuminate. We have added some additional characters: shrub or small tree 3-7 m; heads arranged in short clusters or panicles; involucre with 
<pageBreakToken pageId="12" pageNumber="117" start="start">bracts</pageBreakToken>
in 3-5 series; corolla 10-12 mm long; style branches 0.7-1 mm long; pappus up to 6.5 mm. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. obtusata" pageId="12" pageNumber="117" rank="species" species="obtusata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="117">G. obtusata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the following: leaves broadly elliptic, apex broadly rounded to obtuse, not mucronate, 4.5-20 mm 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-13 mm; involucre 6.5-7.5 mm tall, involucral bracts acute to sharply acuminate; style branches 0.5-0.7 mm long. Additional characters for 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. obtusata" pageId="12" pageNumber="117" rank="species" species="obtusata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="117">G. obtusata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
include: shrub of 1.0-2.6 m; heads glomerate at tips of branches and in clusters of 1-several in the subterminal axils; involucre with bracts in 5-6 series; corollas 6.5-7.5 mm long; pappus up to 7.5 mm long. In the field 
<pageBreakToken pageId="13" pageNumber="118" start="start">the</pageBreakToken>
difference is striking with the larger more robust 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. hypoleuca" pageId="13" pageNumber="118" rank="species" species="hypoleuca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="118">G. hypoleuca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
contrasting with the smaller, more compact 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. obtusata" pageId="13" pageNumber="118" rank="species" species="obtusata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="118">G. obtusata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore we have chosen to recognize 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. obtusata" pageId="13" pageNumber="118" rank="species" species="obtusata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="118">G. obtusata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a separate species.
</paragraph>
